<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E7FF31FF25FC71FD87BA53" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E7FF31FF25FC71FAD6BB8A" blockId="176.[151,1436,948,1656]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FF25FC71FEB2BB3A" bold="true" box="[199,332,1020,1045]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FEB6FC70FE0DBB3B" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[340,499,1020,1044]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FEB6FC70FE0DBB3B" box="[340,499,1020,1044]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the same general habitus as 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FC85FC70FC28BB3B" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[871,982,1020,1044]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FC85FC70FC28BB3B" box="[871,982,1020,1044]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both female 
<typeStatus id="044B9BE297E7FF31FB95FC70FB4CBB3A" box="[1143,1202,1021,1045]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">types</typeStatus>
resemble each other in details, even in the shapes of the seventh abdominal sternite and the subgenital plate. The synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FA66FBACFEF8BB73" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrifrons">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FA66FBACFEF8BB73" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. nigrifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FEA7FBC8FE4DBB73" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[325,435,1092,1116]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FEA7FBC8FE4DBB73" box="[325,435,1092,1116]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is thus correct. Both taxa are with certainty only known from females. Although 
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E7FF31FAA2FBC8FF1FBBAF" author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." pageId="176" pageNumber="177" pagination="247 - 394" refId="ref184452" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1888) Monographie der Stenopelmatiden und Gryllacriden. Verhandlungen der Zoologisch- Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 38, 247 - 394, pls 5 - 9." type="journal article" year="1888">Brunner (1888)</bibRefCitation>
mentions also a male in his description of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FD25FBE4FC99BBAF" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[711,871,1128,1152]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FD25FBE4FC99BBAF" box="[711,871,1128,1152]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, he only gives the measurements for the female. I did not find a male in NHM 
<collectingRegion id="1934EBA297E7FF31FE34FB01FDECBB8A" box="[470,530,1164,1189]" country="Austria" name="Wien" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Wien</collectingRegion>
fitting Brunner's description that was collected before his monograph.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E7FF31FF25FB22FD87BA53" blockId="176.[151,1436,948,1656]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">
The situation of the male described by 
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E7FF31FD7AFB3DFCBEBBE7" author="Karny, H. H." box="[664,832,1200,1224]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" pagination="35 - 186" refId="ref187759" refString="Karny, H. H. (1929 a) Revisionen der Gryllacriden des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien einschliesslich der Collection Brunner V. Wattenwyl, 1. Halfte. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 43, 35 - 186, Taf. 4 - 6." type="journal article" year="1929">Karny (1929a)</bibRefCitation>
as (&quot; 
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FC61FB3CFA99BBE7" box="[899,1383,1200,1224]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FC61FB3CFB83BBE7" authority="Br." authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[899,1149,1200,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrifrons">Eremus nigrifrons Br.</taxonomicName>
=? 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FB5DFB3DFA99BBE7" authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" box="[1215,1383,1200,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">basalis Walker</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
det. Karny&quot;) is different. It certainly represents another species that differs from both female 
<typeStatus id="044B9BE297E7FF31FB7AFB58FB28BBC2" box="[1176,1238,1237,1261]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">types</typeStatus>
. It comes from a different and quite remote locality in 
<collectingRegion id="1934EBA297E7FF31FDAAFB7AFD2DBA3F" box="[584,723,1271,1296]" country="India" name="Tamil Nadu" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Tamil Nadu</collectingRegion>
, while the 
<typeStatus id="044B9BE297E7FF31FCB6FB75FC7ABA3F" box="[852,900,1272,1296]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FC4DFB74FBDFBA3F" box="[943,1057,1272,1296]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FC4DFB74FBDFBA3F" box="[943,1057,1272,1296]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is from 
<collectingCountry id="A3E765D097E7FF31FB67FB7AFB18BA3F" box="[1157,1254,1271,1296]" name="India" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Bombay</collectingCountry>
. The subgenital plate of that male is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E7FF31FDDBFA90FCECBA1A" authority="Bol." authorityName="Bolivar" authorityYear="1900" box="[569,786,1308,1333]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegantulus">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FDDBFA90FD27BA1B" box="[569,729,1308,1332]" italics="true" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">E. elegantulus</emphasis>
Bol.
</taxonomicName>
, but has the wide basal area longer and the rounded apical lobes only half as long as the wide basal area (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E7FF31FD4AFAB2FCF0BA77" box="[680,782,1343,1368]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Fig. 61E</figureCitation>
). This specimen requires a more severe re-examination to be certain about its exact taxonomic status.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E7FF31FF25FA0AFABEB957" pageId="176" pageNumber="177" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E7FF31FF25FA0AFD28BAEA" blockId="176.[151,1436,948,1656]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E7FF31FF25FA0AFEA7BA8F" bold="true" box="[199,345,1415,1440]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Description.</emphasis>
Medium sized species (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E7FF31FD8DFA0AFD33BA8F" box="[623,717,1415,1440]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="174.[151,250,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@174.[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetPageId="174" captionText="FIGURE 60. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–E, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (C–D) and female (E); F–G, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; H, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; I–J, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female type BrW17.124.—Lateral view (A, C, E–F, H–I), dorsal view (B, D, G, J). Scale 10 mm (Brunner's types not to scale)." pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Figs. 60</figureCitation>
F–H). Head rather wide; face impressed punctate, black, ocelli yellow, clypeus and labrum light brown (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E7FF31FD81FA21FD34BAEA" box="[611,714,1452,1477]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Fig. 61C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E7FF31FF25FA42FE89BAC7" blockId="176.[151,1436,948,1656]" box="[199,375,1487,1512]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Male unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E7FF31FF25FA79FABEB957" blockId="176.[151,1436,948,1656]" pageId="176" pageNumber="177">
Female. Seventh abdominal sternite at hind margin with a short appendage in middle with strongly stiffened margins surrounding a groove, laterally apical margin of seventh sternite also grooved. Subgenital plate consisting of a roughly triangular central part with convex margins and obtuse tip and a shorter conical lateral part at both sides (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E7FF31FF3CF9D2FE91B957" box="[222,367,1631,1656]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Figs. 61D, F</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor elongate, slightly curved throughout; tip unmodified, acute (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E7FF31FB46F9D2FACDB957" box="[1188,1331,1631,1656]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="174.[151,250,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@174.[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetPageId="174" captionText="FIGURE 60. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–E, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (C–D) and female (E); F–G, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; H, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; I–J, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female type BrW17.124.—Lateral view (A, C, E–F, H–I), dorsal view (B, D, G, J). Scale 10 mm (Brunner's types not to scale)." pageId="176" pageNumber="177">Figs. 60F, H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
